<DOC><DOCNO> AP880817-0082 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-17-88 0729EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-SouthKorea-Arrests     08-17 0196</FIRST><SECOND>PM-South Korea-Arrests,0201</SECOND><HEAD>Police Charge 52 Students With Pro-Unification Marches</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Police today charged 52 students withleading violent protests during marches supporting reunificationtalks with North Korean students.   Police said the students were accused of violating the NationalSecurity Law or laws banning violent protests.   Police said about 8,260 people, mostly students, have been takeninto custody since radical students began scattered protests Aug. 7to press for unification talks with North Korean students.   North and South Korean students called for the talks in theborder truce village of Panmunjom to mark the Aug. 15 anniversaryof Korea's liberation from Japan in 1945.   But police, determined to prevent disturbances before theupcoming Olympics in Seoul, enforced stringent security measuresand blocked all student marches and rallies advocating the bordertalks.   All but 252 detained were released after warnings, with only 200of them still under investigations, police said.   Police said 705 policemen and 45 protesters were injured, butstudent sources claimed the number of students injured was muchhigher.   The Korean Peninsula has been divided since the end of World WarII between the communist North and the capitalist South.</TEXT></DOC>